2015-2018 MLB Pitch Data¶

by Andrew Schutte¶

Investigation Overview¶

I want to visualize the pitches throw by MLB pitcher, Zack Greinke. This includes the pitch speeds, pitch location and the results of each pitch/atbat.

Dataset Overview¶

This dataset was scrapped from MLB Gameday data. I got the dataset from Kaggle. This provides a lot of data and information on each pitch. For more information, read this link.

Histogram of Pitch Start Speeds¶

This shows the frequency of the start speed for all of Greinke's pitches. This distribution is affected by the fact that Greinke throws 6 different pitches. These 6 different pitches vary his overall start speeds. We do see a spike in frequency around 90 MPH. There's a good chance that the most common pitch he throws starts with a speed around 90.

In [3]:
plt.figure(figsize= (16,8))

plt.ylabel('# of pitches');
plt.xlabel('Start pitch speed in MPH');
plt.title('Frequency of pitch start speeds');

Histogram of Pitch End Speeds¶

This shows the frequency of the start speed for all of Greinke's pitches. His 6 different pitches also have varying end speeds. This looks similar to the previous histogram, but notice the x axis labels. The histogram is shifted 5 or so miles per hour to the left. This is because the pitch speeds down as it goes from the pitcher to the plate. We see a similar spike to start speed, but it is about 5 MPH slower. This leads us to believe his most common pitch has an end speed around 85 MPH.

Frequency of Pitch Types¶

The histograms are such an odd distribution because each pitch has a different start and end speed range. Lets see what type of pitches Greinke throws. Notice that the four seam fastball is the most common. Back in our histograms, we saw that his most common pitch was around 85-90. We can now assume that is the four seam fastball.

In [5]:
g = sb.catplot(data = df, x = 'pitch_type', kind = 'count', order = df.pitch_type.value_counts().index, color = 'skyblue', height = 8, aspect = 1);

plt.title('Frequency of pitches');

Start and End Speeds by Pitch Type¶

The histograms had a big spread and an odd distribution. Pitch type is really important. Each pitch type has it's own range. We assumed that our four seam fastball was that pitch that gave us such a big leap in the frequency around 90 MPH. We also see the two seam fastball. That pitch isn't as common, but we see the start speed and end speed is roughly the same as his four seam. The two seam is also supposed to move more than a four seam. It is also important to notice the start and end speeds of the other pitches. Greinke has a good speed difference across each of his unique pitch types.

Pitch Result with Pitch Type¶

The dataset has a code for each pitch's individual result. We should look at the percentage pitch type usage for each pitch result. One interesting insight is that Greinke uses his slider to get swings and misses low, but the pitch is also a ball in the dirt often. Greinke also gets a lot of called strikes with his fastball, and a lot of swinging strikes with his slider. He throws these the pitches the most and they are highly effective.

In [7]:
p_table = pd.pivot_table(df,index='code',columns='pitch_type',aggfunc='size')
p_table = p_table.div(p_table.sum(axis=1), axis=0)
ax = p_table.plot.barh(stacked=True, figsize=(12,8), color = ['tomato', 'orange','dodgerblue','lightblue','navy', 'hotpink'])
ax.legend(bbox_to_anchor=(1,1));
plt.title('Pitch Results w/ Pitch Type %');
plt.ylabel('Result Type');
plt.xlabel('% of Total Pitches per Result');

At Bat Results with Pitch Type¶

Let's look at the at bat results with pitch types. We can draw conclusions about which pitches work for Greinke. Greinke uses his slider for a lot of strike outs. This builds off our last visual where we saw Greinke gets a lot of swing and misses on his slider. It is also good to note that he has more strike outs than any other atbat result. This is impressive, but he can also get outs many other ways. If we were to combine fly out and ground out, that would be a higher total than his strikeouts. Nonetheless, Greinke is still impressive.

In [8]:
eve = dfEvent.event.value_counts().index
code = df.code.value_counts().index
pi_type = CategoricalDtype(categories=["FF","FT","SL" ,"CH", "CU", "EP"],ordered=True)
ev_type = CategoricalDtype(categories=eve, ordered=True)
co_type = CategoricalDtype(categories=code, ordered=True)
dfEvent.pitch_type = dfEvent.pitch_type.astype(pi_type)
df.pitch_type = df.pitch_type.astype(pi_type)
dfEvent.event = dfEvent.event.astype(ev_type)
df.code = df.code.astype(co_type)
c = pd.crosstab(dfEvent['event'], dfEvent['pitch_type'])
#c.sort_values(by = dfEvent.event,ascending=False)
ax = c.plot.barh(stacked=True,  figsize=(12,8),color = ['tomato', 'orange','dodgerblue','lightblue','navy', 'hotpink'])
ax.legend(bbox_to_anchor=(1,1));
plt.title('Atbat Results w/ Pitch Type Counts');
plt.ylabel('Result Type');
plt.xlabel('Count of Total Pitches per Type per Result');
plt.show()

Four Seam Fastball Location Heat Map¶

This is interesting to see where Greinke throws his fastball. He throws it a lot on the right side of the plate. (View from the catcher). The black square is the average strike zone. Anything inside of the box is usually a strike. Human error is often prevalent in baseball.

Two Seam Fastball Location Heat Map¶

This is interesting to see where Greinke throws his two seam fastball. He throws it a lot in the lower left corner of the strike zone. (View from the catcher). This pitch moves from right to left for Greinke. This movement makes the best location for this pitch in that lower left corner. It can look like it starts in the strike zone but then moves out of the zone.

Change Up Location Heat Map¶

This is interesting to see where Greinke throws his change up. He seems to have very good control of it and is really consistent. He throws it a lot in the lower left corner of the strike zone and sometimes below the strike zone.(View from the catcher). This pitch drops and is much slower than his fastball. Throwing this pitch low is a great strategy. The pitch looks like it is in the zone, then drops down at the last second.

Curveball Location Heat Map¶

This is interesting to see where Greinke throws his curveball. He throws it a lot in the bottom middle of the strike zone and sometimes below the strike zone.(View from the catcher). His curveball breaks from left to right in a sweeping motion. This makes locating this pitch in the middle of the strike zone and down effective. The pitch can start as a ball and then drop right in.

Slider Location Heat Map¶

This is interesting to see where Greinke throws his change up. He seems to have very good control of it and is really consistent. He throws it a lot in the lower right corner of the strike zone and sometimes below the strike zone.(View from the catcher). This location and pitch type is very effective against most hitters. The pitch will move from left to right, but faster and more extreme than his curveball. This pitch looks similar to a fastball but then drops down to the right.

Nasty Factory by Location¶

The nasty factor is how good the pitch is. It uses a number of variables to calculate this. It isn't a real stat, but it is cool to look at. We see that the nastiest pitches (green) are towards the corners of the strike zone (the black rectangle). This is much like some of the sliders and change ups that he throws.
